                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>At 10:30 p. m. on December 15, President Truman delivered a radio and television
                    address to the American people announcing his intention to declare the existence
                    of a state of national emergency on the following day. He stated that the United
                    States was willing to negotiate if the Communists were, but would not yield to
                    aggression nor engage in appeasement in the face of the great danger created by
                    the rulers of the Soviet Union. The President announced plans to increase
                    defense production, expand the armed forces, and establish wage and price
                    controls. On December 16, the Office of Defense Mobilization was set up to
                    direct and coordinate the mobilization efforts of the government. (<hi
                        rend="italic">Public Papers of the Presidents of the United States: Harry S.
                        Truman, 1950</hi>, page 741)</p>
            </div>
